PiperOrigin-RevId: 386875733
Change-Id: I6fcd680101df3f2f0371a561d15e7821dab16ebc","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/fedf28cc0dc72e2b69dbe5700f8049a34d1dc746"},{"sha":"02c1e5ab6aa9e21ed987fb2a5d91d9e6114f8705","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Fuse handling of trailing tiles into the main loop nest in transpose implementation.

Previously we handled trailing partial tiles by using separate loop nests. While this was functionally correct, it turns out to hurt performance, most likely due to poorer locality.

Instead, restructure the loop nest plans to handle trailing partial tiles as part of the main loop nest. Add a special "trailing next node" field that, if set, indicates that a loop should run one more loop iteration on a modified plan pointed to by the trailing next node field. This means that the trailing tile is handled with better locality, rather than coming back to it in a much later loop.

[{"sha":"d2c557b17d497c718f1bcad84c796f9a18182fc8","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: Module move support for AbsResource and AbsResourceInstance

This is a subset of the MoveDestination behavior for AbsResource and
AbsResourceInstance which deals with source and destination addresses that
refer to module calls or module instances.

They both work by delegating to ModuleInstance.MoveDestination and then
applying the same resource or resource instance address to the
newly-chosen module instance address, thus ensuring that when we move
a module we also move all of the resources inside that module in the same
way.

This doesn't yet include support for moving between specific resource or
resource instance addresses; that'll follow later. This commit should have
enough logic to support moving between module names and module instance
keys, including any module calls or resources nested within.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d2c557b17d497c718f1bcad84c796f9a18182fc8"}]

[{"sha":"86af5fd93fc70db185405d2d130850d5d20f7bb3","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Tweak transpose loop ordering and block size selection heuristic.

* Move the code that chooses the loop ordering after the code that chooses a block size.
* When computing the stride of a block dimension, multiply it by the block size. Previously we weren't doing this, which meant we incorrectly though that loops that iterated over blocks had small strides.
* Use `min(a_stride * penalty, b_stride)` instead of `a_stride * penalty + b_stride` as the loop heuristic. If a dimension has a small stride in one array but an enormous stride in another, we probably care more about keeping the small strided accesses together. Empirically this seems to improve benchmarks.
* Tweak block size selection heuristic. Don't use an inner_block_size smaller than the smallest vectorized kernel we have. Also, prefer to visit the entirety of the dimension in a single outer_block if it's small enough.

[{"sha":"4d733b4d2dc16cd5461905da06e00db95bb09698","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: Implement ModuleInstance.MoveDestination

This method encapsulates the move-processing rules for applying move
statements to ModuleInstance addresses. It honors both module call moves
and module instance moves by trying to find a subsequence of the input
that matches the "from" endpoint and then, if found, replacing it with
the "to" endpoint while preserving the prefix and suffix around the match,
if any.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4d733b4d2dc16cd5461905da06e00db95bb09698"},{"sha":"994ee23c06e21932cf9339c04d9ae3fabda0d26e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: Module move support for AbsResource and AbsResourceInstance

This is a subset of the MoveDestination behavior for AbsResource and
AbsResourceInstance which deals with source and destination addresses that
refer to module calls or module instances.

They both work by delegating to ModuleInstance.MoveDestination and then
applying the same resource or resource instance address to the
newly-chosen module instance address, thus ensuring that when we move
a module we also move all of the resources inside that module in the same
way.

This doesn't yet include support for moving between specific resource or
resource instance addresses; that'll follow later. This commit should have
enough logic to support moving between module names and module instance
keys, including any module calls or resources nested within.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/994ee23c06e21932cf9339c04d9ae3fabda0d26e"}]

[{"sha":"386591985f0e7b3eeccaed2357d05fa17c6fa4fe","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Fix issue where disabling TensorFloat-32 had no effect.

The issue was the tensor_float_32_enabled global variable was being linked in the binary twice. Disabling TensorFloat-32 changed one version of the global variable, and OpKernels checking TensorFloat-32 looked at the other version of the global variable. @penpornk helped find the fix.

I confirmed this change fixes the issue when applied to commit 2903b0a7d133a15d71d513df826386dc28d0631f. Unfortunately, the tests did not catch this issue, as the test case in config_test.py currently only supports Ampere and is skipped for non-Ampere GPUs (TensorFloat-32 only supports Ampere). I will later add a test that will catch such issues even when run on non-Ampere GPUs.

I plan on cherry-picking this change into TF 2.6.

Co-authored-by: Penporn Koanantakool‎ <penporn@google.com>

[{"sha":"e95fc647063378993ec84d41cbbda6dcb60bad4e","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Remove special handling for empty or anonymous `shared_name` attribute

Some ops don't follow the common semantics (i.e., empty or anonymous
`shared_name` guaranteeing unique allocated resources) so we can't utilize those
semantics in resource alias analysis. See e.g. `FusedResizeAndPadConvFunctor`.
Also added warning about resource-allocating ops that are treated conservatively
in resource alias analysis.
